The Hohe Domkirche St. Peter in Trier is the oldest Episcopal Church in Germany and the mother Church of the diocese of Trier. With a length of 112.5 meters and a width of 41 meters, the significant sacred building of Western architecture is the largest Church building in the city of Trier.Since 1986, the Cathedral of Trier is part of the UNESCO world heritage Roman monuments, Cathedral and liebfrauen Church in Trier, the Further he is a protected cultural property under the Hague Convention.Cathedral Of Trier
The Cathedral stands on the remains of a splendid Roman house. In the Wake of the Emperor Constantine, initiated the "Constantinian turning point" to Christianity, was built a Basilica, which was under the Bishop Maximin (329-346) to one of the largest Church facilities in Europe with four basilicas, a baptistery and several outbuildings expanded. 340 the so-called Quadratbau, the core of the dome with four monumental columns from the Odenwald (Domstein).
As the core of the medieval settlement of the Cathedral of Trier was since 1843 in the interest of archaeological research. Larger excavations took place, especially after the Second world war, under the Director of the Episcopal Cathedral and diocesan Museum, Theodor K. Kempf, and his successor, Winfried Weber to 1981. In the oldest layers of the on-site noble Roman residential quarter of the 2 could. and 3. Century ad are found. This includes, among other things, a realm with wall - and ceiling paintings decorated ceremonial room with cassette.Erika Simon: The Constantine ceiling paintings in Trier. Zabern, Mainz 1986, ISBN 3-8053-0903-1 (Trier contributions to antiquity customer 3). Under the present transept of the Cathedral, parts of the building are preserved, the reconstructed frescoes in the Cathedral and diocesan Museum. The rich amenities has led to the fact that the plant is attributed in part to a late antique Palace construction.The residential development was built in the early 4. Century, demolished and leveled. In its place was built a double Church with two East-facing, three-aisled basilicas, of which the column positions have been detected. The pillars of the North Basilica consisted of Odenwald granite,to be Precise, actually a Mela-quartz diorite, see Erwin Nickel: Odenwald. The front of the Odenwald between Darmstadt and Heidelberg. Bornträger, Berlin/ Stuttgart, 1985 (collection of geological guides 65) p. 20. what today is still in front of the Cathedral lying Domstein points. The Domstein very similar pillar is in the late-Roman stone quarries in the sea of rock in the Lauter valley. The expansion of the two Church plants, including the cross-structures and Peristylhöfe is not completely secured, and was probably between 40 (North Basilica) and 30 m (Südbasilika under the present Church of our lady) in width with a length of 150 m. Between the two churches, a square baptistery, which is marked today in the pavement of the Domfreihofs was. In front of the choir of the North Basilica octagonal building remains were uncovered, which was interpreted by the excavators as Mr memory (a storage place for relics).Towards the end of the fourth century, the Northern Basilica was rebuilt after it was destroyed again and in the area of the crossing a Quadratbau with a side length of 41.5 m built. In the middle of this building is an elevated Podium, at the four corners have been used as a replacement for fire broken granite columns, re-used columns (spolia]) from limestone. The decoration of the capitals, they could have come from the temple of the Lord in Brno.Heinz cuppers, in: H. cuppers (ed.): The Romans in Rhineland-Palatinate. P. 593. Along the wind street on the North side of the Cathedral, the associated brick masonry up to a height of 30 m is visible.To see the Roman buildings, the Cathedral of Trier Hans-Peter Kuhnen: Dom and loving women: the beginnings of The Trier Bishop's Church. In: H.-P. Kuhnen (Hrsg.): Roman Trier. Theiss, Stuttgart, 2001, (leader to archaeological monuments in Germany, 40), p. 114-121; Winfried Weber: ancient Church in the area of Dom and loving women. In: Heinz Cuppers (Ed.): The Romans in Rhineland-Palatinate. P. 633f.; Sabine Faust: Dom and loving women: early Christian Church to the new. In: Rheinisches Landesmuseum Trier (Hrsg.): Leader to archaeological monuments of the Trierer country. Trier 2008, (publication series of the Rhenish land Museum of Trier 35) p. 44f.
Means alterdie Church plant of the 4. Century was destroyed by the Franks, the Quadratbau and the Northern Basilica rebuilt. Further destruction took place can 882 by the Normans.From the office of the Bishop Egbert, the Cathedral was expanded and redesigned. The West façade is a typical example of the architecture under the Saliern. The Western choir was consecrated in 1121.Exterior changes brought the end of the middle ages. Archbishop Balduin of Luxembourg was around 1350, the two Osttürme increase and Archbishop Richard von Greiffenklau to increase Vollrads after 1512 the southwest tower, because the tower of the parish Church of St. Gangolf dominates the ' Dom ' Church tower.
Modern times at the beginning of the 18th century. Century, the earlier planned heiltum chapel, the monumental structure with a pilgrim stairs in the Interior of the Ostchores, was grown. There, the Holy robe is kept. After a fire of the roof on the 17. In August 1717 the Cathedral from 1719 to 1723, it was remodelled by Johann Georg Judas, and received the cross house, the Osttürme were provided with a Baroque dome.In the 19th century. Century were made several restorations, which had set itself the target of the medieval appearance of to restore; so you replaced in 1883, the Baroque dome of the Osttürme by neo-Gothic. In the Second world war, the Kordeler sand stone of the existing Cathedral was seriously damaged, but could be built relatively quickly.From 1960 to 1974, he was thoroughly restored, and on 1. May 1974, re-opened.Above the Church clock in the elevated South-East tower of the Latin Text "nescitis qua hora dominus veniet" (ye know not at what hour the Lord will), a reference to the Bible passage "vigilate ergo quia nescitis qua hora Dominus vester venturus sit" (Wake up! Because you do not know on what day your Lord is coming). According to a legend, it is in the Tradition of the quarrel between Bishop and city in response to the Text on the tower of St. Gangolf, where it says "vigilate et orate!" (Watch and pray!), a number of times in the New Testament, used turn.On 4. May 2008 was held the first beatification in the Cathedral of Trier. Blessed mother Rosa, the founder of the forest wide Bacher Franciscan was spoken of inside of the blessed virgin Mary of the angels.
Relics and GrabmälerDer sacred Rock is the most famous relic in the Cathedral Treasury. It is kept in a cultivation under a protective glass in a wood container and only very rarely presented to the Public, similar to the shroud of Turin.In the Cathedral, numerous tombs of former archbishops of Trier, such as Balduin of Luxembourg, Richard of Greiffenklau to Vollrads and Theodoric of Wied.With the Andreas-Tragaltar of the Bishop Egbert of Trier Cathedral has one of the most important works of art ottonian goldsmiths ' art.An ivory plaque of Oriental origin, which had served as the side wall of a reliquary box and the emergence of most of the to researchers to 6. Century, is dated, is not in a confined space to less than 65 persons between the two monumental buildings.Balthasar Fischer: The ivory tablet of Trier Cathedral Treasury. In: Kur-Trier, Spanish Yearbook 1969, hrg from the city library of Trier and the society for useful research, 9. Born in 1969. Printing and publishing New & co., Trier in 1969. P. 5ff.
The swallow's nest organ at the Trier Cathedral is an Instrument of the Bonn-based Organ Builder Klais, it was at the same time with the renovated Cathedral on 1. May 1974 dedicated. The Cathedral organist Wolfgang Oehms created MRP consists of 67 registers, four manuals and Pedal and the playing of organ music of all stylistic periods to the avant-garde.In the base of the organ is a representation of the shepherd God Pan as the inventor of the pan flute, if you like a primitive predecessor of the organ that can be worked out by the organist from the housing, and five own sounds wants to play. The figure can music be interpreted because of their horns as a devil, was forced by an organ Builder, for the glory of God; a truly harmonious music, but the devil is not possible, and the five pipes of the pan flute are out of tune considerably:
